There is another form of reasoning, sometimes called Dilemma, which is also a hypotheticodisjunctive reasoning, but which, instead of having the major promise hypothetical¹ and the minor disjunctive, has both combined in the major; theothole of the disjunctive consequente being denied in the minor. E. g. “If A is B, either C is D, or Eis F; but neither C is D, nor Ε is F; therefore A is not B.'' This form is given by Wallis, lib. iii. cap. 19.; as well as by Wolf and Kant. But it is a perversiori of the Dilemma. proper, and introduces no distinction whatever; being merely a common disjunctive syllogismos is shewn by Wallis himself. Itis, in fact, the enumeratio, not the complexio, of Cicero.
